definitions.definition: Not inside or within a place , especially a place that someone or something was formerly inside or is customarily inside:
examples: I worked away cleaning the U-bend until all the gunge was out .
This building is unsafe. Keep out !

subdefinitions.definition: Not at home , or not at one's office or place of employment .
examples: I'm sorry, Mr Smith is out at the moment.

subdefinitions.definition: Not in jail , prison , or captivity ; freed from confinement .
examples: Sentenced to five years, he could be out in three with good behavior.

subdefinitions.definition: Not fitted or inserted into something.
examples: The TV won't work with the plug out !

subdefinitions.definition: Falling or passing or being situated beyond the bounds of the playing area.
examples: I thought the ball hit the line, but the umpire said it was out .
labels: of the ball or other playing implement
subdefinitions.label_groups: sports , of the ball or other playing implement

definitions.definition: Not (or no longer) acceptable or in consideration , play , availability , or operation :

subdefinitions.definition: Dismissed from play under the rules of the game.
examples: He bowls, Johnson pokes at it ... and ... Johnson is out ! Caught behind by Ponsonby!
labels: used especially of a batsman or batter in cricket or baseball
subdefinitions.label_groups: in various games; used especially of a batsman or batter in cricket or baseball

examples: Right, so that idea's out . Let's move on to the next one.
I've got diabetes, so cookies are right out .
Power is out in the entire city.
My wi-fi is out .
subdefinitions.label_groups: of certain services, devices, or facilities

subdefinitions.definition: Not having availability of a service , such as power or communications .
examples: Most of the city got service back yesterday, but my neighborhood is still out .
labels: of a user of a service
subdefinitions.label_groups: of a user of a service

examples: I called round to the house but all the lights were out and no one was home.

subdefinitions.definition: Temporarily not in operation , or not being attended as usual.
examples: School is out tomorrow due to snow. When college is out for the summer, I'll head back to my home state.
when school gets out today After school's out , I go to the library until my mom gets off work.
I had a whack on the head and was out for a few seconds.

subdefinitions.definition: No longer popular or in fashion .
examples: Black is out this season. The new black is white.

subdefinitions.definition: Openly acknowledging that one is LGBT+ ( gay , trans , etc).
examples: It's no big deal to be out in the entertainment business.

subdefinitions.definition: Open , public ; public about or openly acknowledging some (usually specified) identity .

examples: My secret is out .

definitions.definition: Available to be seen , or to be interacted with in some way:

subdefinitions.definition: Released , available for purchase , download or other use.
examples: Did you hear? Their newest CD is out !
The garden looks beautiful now that the roses are out .

subdefinitions.definition: Visible in the sky; not obscured by clouds.
examples: The sun is out , and it's a lovely day.
subdefinitions.label_groups: of the sun, moon or stars

subdefinitions.definition: Of a young lady: having entered society and available to be courted .

definitions.definition: At or near its lowest level .
examples: You can walk to the island when the tide's out .

definitions.definition: Without ; no longer in possession of; not having any more.
examples: Do you have any bread? Sorry, we're out .

definitions.definition: Containing errors or discrepancies , or in error by a stated amount.
examples: Nothing adds up in this report. All these figures are out .
The measurement was out by three millimetres.
